item.title: I thought it was a cicada
item.description:
Decided to record this, because I thought I'd flip him off his back the little guy would fly away.
I was able to check on him quite a few times during my shift. Dunken Donuts sugar packets and bottled OSHA required jobsite water bottles. Assumed he'd be gone once he filled his stomach and warmed up.
Shift was over, little guy was still right where I left em. So I took him home! I was not prepared for the amount of work Hummingbirds take. THESE ARE NOT PETS, these little fucks have to hibernate every night, called Torpor, or they'd starve during the night.
48hrs after I found him, decided things were not right and it's time to get him some help. Took him to a man, whom I will call Hummingbird Jim, gave him all the cash in my pocket and left him in far more capable hands than I. Jim told me he was just a baby, probably had just molted his adult plumage but was still too baby to fly and feed for himself. Two weeks later Hummingbird Jim let me know that he had released 5 hummingbirds back into the wild, and my little guy was one of them. I now keep a feeder on my front porch, many hummers have come to visit. I hope he is one of them :)

item.title: Kestrel Windhover, or Kiting
item.description: Kestrels are often identified by their iconic flying behaviour – giving it one of its old nicknames: the 'windhover'. The kestrel has the incredible ability to keep its head still while hovering in a single spot to pinpoint its prey. They hover by flying into the oncoming wind at the same speed as the air current. In fact, they're flying forward, but the wind resistance creates a hovering effect. As such, kestrels have slightly stiffer feathers than other birds of prey to withstand these strong winds.
